{
  "narration": "You descend the steps with deliberate slowness, arms raised, posture open and unthreatening as you approach the wary bandits. The firelight flickers across your features, and the heaviness in your words draws both the attention and suspicion of Captain Gorvek and the last crossbowman. Gorvek narrows his eyes, his scarred face twisted in a sneer. 'A soldier, you say? I knew the look. Don't suppose your faith will save you here, priest.'\n\nAs you talk, you angle your body just enough, keeping Gorvek's gaze locked on you and forcing the crossbowman's focus to shift back and forth. Your calm, measured steps and earnest tone draw the camp's eyes to you, giving Kira the opening she needs.\n\nIn the shadows behind the crates, Kira's eyes catch yours; she nods imperceptibly and melts into the gloom, moving with the silence of a night breeze. The crossbowman's attention flickers, uncertain, as your words ring out over the crackle of the fire. Gorvek remains fixed on you, jaw clenched, the unnatural gleam in his eyes seeming to pulse with suspicion and something darker.\n\nKira rolls Stealth: d20 (18) + 6 = 24. She is utterly unseen as she circles behind the crossbowman, her shortsword ready for one last deadly strike. The crossbowman, tense and shifting his aim between you and the darkness, remains oblivious.\n\nGorvek spits into the fire. 'You picked a poor night for confessions, soldier. You got one chance to tell me who sent you, before I send you to meet your gods.'\n\nYou sense the moment is right: with all eyes on you and Kira in perfect position, the final confrontation is at hand. Do you keep talking to buy Kira more time, or do you spring the trap and let her strike? The stronghold's fate hangs in the balance, and your old soldier's courage burns steady in your chest.",
